WEBVTT

1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:10,000
Dr. Rivera: Welcome to our final check-in. What has stayed with you from the whole program?

2
00:00:11,500 --> 00:00:30,000
Participant A: I think the biggest shift is how I relate to pain itself. When I really sit with what I used to call pain I can see it's actually many different sensations — pressure, heat, a kind of buzzing — and they're always changing. Calling it all one thing called pain was making it feel permanent and monolithic.

3
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:44,000
Dr. Rivera: What you're describing — that the category pain dissolves into distinct, impermanent sensations — that IS the reappraisal the whole program is building toward. That's the transformation we hoped for.

4
00:00:45,500 --> 00:01:02,000
Participant B: For me it's the watching. I'm so much better at noticing when my mind is doing something — like catastrophizing or avoiding — rather than just being inside it. I noticed myself getting anxious about an upcoming appointment and could just watch that without being dragged into it.

5
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:15,000
Dr. Rivera: That observer capacity is metacognition fully internalized. How will you use these skills when a real pain flare hits outside of practice?

6
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:30,000
Participant A: My plan is to pause, get curious about what exactly I'm feeling, break it down the way we practiced, and then decide what to do. Not react from the whole overwhelming blob.

7
00:01:31,500 --> 00:01:43,000
Participant B: And I want to remember the labeling technique. It's amazing how just saying there is fear or there is tension gives me a little distance from it. I feel less owned by it.

8
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:55,000
Dr. Rivera: Psychoeducation point — that distance is what the research calls defusion. It's not suppression, it's a different mode of awareness. Pain is still real; your relationship to it has changed.

9
00:01:56,500 --> 00:02:05,000
Participant A: Early in the program I was just consumed. The pain was all I could focus on. Now it's still there but I'm also there. There's room for both.

10
00:02:06,500 --> 00:02:17,500
Dr. Rivera: That's a profound statement. The pain hasn't necessarily gone away, but you've enlarged the container. That is the goal of this program.

11
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Participant B: Honestly at first when the flares hit I would breathe hard and try to muscle through, just push the feeling away. Now I don't do that. I stay with it. It's completely different.

12
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:42,000
Dr. Rivera: That shift from avoidance to presence is the entire arc. You've both covered it. I'm very glad you're leaving with these tools. Use them.

13
00:02:43,500 --> 00:02:52,000
Participant A: Thank you. This changed how I think about my body.

14
00:02:53,500 --> 00:03:00,000
Participant B: Same. I feel like I have something now that's actually mine.

15
00:03:01,500 --> 00:03:08,000
Dr. Rivera: That's exactly right. It's yours to keep. Take good care.

